<font color="#FF0000">TO COOK</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct 18  7:10:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
It seems that there is a &quot;whole page full&quot; of stuff since I last responded to you. Before I read it, I will respond to you while my ideas are fresh.<br><br>
Your way of looking at the war as being a small battle in the Cold War against communism that led to communism's eventual defeat is not a unique way of thinking. I have heard it before, and I don't really have a problem with it. Surprised?<br><br>
The real catch, however, is that you are looking back 30 years in hindsight.<br><br>
The argument I am posing is that which is in the context of the 1960's. I am not going to pose these arguments again, except to say that the question will always remain, &quot;Was Ho a part of the &quot;Communist Dominion&quot; you speak of, or was he a nationalist?<br><br>
Today, we have troops in Korea, Haiti, and different parts of Europe (Bosnia). A few years ago we fought a very successful war in the Gulf. The Gulf War had a clear cut mission: get Iraqi forces out of Kuwait. An underlying &quot;mission&quot;, which in my opinion - *in hindsight* - was used to win approval of the war from Americans, was the promise of democracy for the people of Kuwait. The last I heard there is no democracy there.<br><br>
It is true that many protested our presence before our troops landed in Bosnia. Little has been done to mollify those opposed to this presence. If we were to pull out today or next year, or five years from now would the region remain stable? I doubt it. Is the solution for us to be in every Somalia in the capacity of &quot;meals on wheels&quot; as Rush Limbaugh calls it? Should we send young American men and women to die in the Rwandas? Yes, millions died in SE Asia after 1975. If I were to read your mind, I would guess that your next statement would be: &quot;Where were the protests against that?&quot; That is a good and logical question. However, we could, in the context of today, ask about the absence of protest about all the other injustices and casualties in other parts of the world that are taking place today. <br><br>
Maybe our friend Joe Delava has some numbers on the exact number of wars which are going on in the world today. I bet we would be surprised.<br><br>
As far as understanding Vietnam and teaching those too young to remember, *we* have to remember what was happening at that time. <br><br>
I don't share your opinion that God sanctioned Vietnam as a Holy War, either.<br><br>
In order to pass judgment on those who protested in the 1960's one has to have the ability to see into their hearts. There were many different reasons to protest, in my view. <br><br>
I don't have the ability to look into people's hearts, but God does. He will judge.<br><br>

<p><code>-- Rainbow@Tennessee. Y'all come  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


